  <Vertical id="ai_intervention_brainstorming_prompt"><Markdown>
We need advice on a psychological intervention using operant conditioning.
          
Annie's roommate is babysitting a six-year-old boy, and has been having
trouble getting him to go to bed. He keeps running away, laughing, or doing
other things that delay bedtime. We tried to put together an intervention
plan that uses positive reinforcement, but it didn't quite work, so we put
together a more complicated plan that changes the antecedent conditions as
well as the consequent conditions. Here's our description of that plan:
      </Markdown>
      <Use ref="intervention_email" />
      <Markdown>
Here is what happened when Annie's roommate tried to implement the plan:
          
The boy went to bed on time the first couple of times, but then bedtime
got later and later. The six-year-old's escape behaviors actually got worse.
          
When we checked on what Annie's roommate was actually doing, we learned
that she was having trouble adhering to the plan. Specifically, we found out
that sometimes she forgets to do the warning countdown and timer, she often 
forgets the small bedtime reward, and often falls into negotiating or arguing
when he whines for extended time.

Given the problems that Annie's roommate is having getting the boy to bed
on time, what advice should we give her to help her improve her adherence
to the intervention plan?
      </Markdown></Vertical>

